What is Dorling Cartogram?

  • A Dorling cartogram replaces polygons by circles with radii in proportion to a numerical thematic variable like population, birth rate, etc.

  • It is an abstract display of areal data that maintains neither shape or topology.

Original algorithm

  • Dorling (1996) proposed the Circular Cartogram
    • Per iteration, the algorithm
    • Computes the repelling and attracting force for each circle
    • Moves circles with restrictions

Software applications

  • Bostock (2010)
    • Pseudo-cartogram for D3.js
  • Cheng (2014)
    • R package cartogram
  • Rudis and Rajerison (2018)
    • R package spdorling
    • Creating Dorling Cartograms from shapefiles
  • Bedward, Eppstein, and Menzel (2018)
    • R package packcircles
    • Adopted the circle packing algorithm by Collins and Stephenson (2003)

Limitations of the original algorithm

  • Need large number of iterations
  • Crowded circles are easily misplaced

Example of misplacement (status 0)

Example of misplacement (status 1)

New triangle-based approach

  • Goal
    • Avoiding misplacement
    • Reducing iterations
  • Idea
    • Starting with non-contiguous circles
    • Pulling them together recursively
    • Using triangles to keep topology
  • Strategy
    • Linking circles by neighbors to construct triangles
    • Choosing two center circles (an edge) to start recursion
    • Calculating the pulling direction by the original triangle median

Limitations

  • The choice of centers
    • Recursive chain reaction
  • Pulling direction decision
    • The slope of triangle median does not change as the opposite edge moves.

Summary and future work

  • Summary
    • Limitations of Dorling cartogram
    • Triangle-based approach
  • Future work
    • Automatic center selection
    • Multiple centers initialization
    • Pulling direction flexibility
